1. How did the researchers go about validating a person's claim to a religion? What I mean, is, there are many people who claim Christianity, and yet are simply &quot;Sunday&quot; Christians. They don't pick up a Bible unless they are sitting in a pew, they don't practice what they hear preached, and they simply view it as a &quot;religion&quot; rather than a life-style or relationship with God. This alone could count for a vast number of divorces coming from &quot;religious&quot; people. I will have to agree with Heather, here, in that people that are truly committed to God (whether that be &quot;main-stream&quot; Christian, LDS, or even Jewish) probably have a stronger committment to their marriage and making it work than those who see divorce as something they can do when the going gets tough (ie: those who simply go to church to say they go to church).<br>
2. Did the people who got a divorce say when they got it? Meaning, most of those religions mentioned have many people who converted at some point in time ... it could very well be that they were divorced before their conversion, now are of a certain belief/religion, and when asked if they had ever been divorced answered yes. So, just because they are now Presbytarian (sp?) doesn't mean they had any church affiliation or committment before their divorce. (Again, also see my comment on those who are only &quot;Sunday&quot; Christians.)<br>
