<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>1. How did the researchers go about validating a person's claim to a religion?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think many who consider themselves religious (like my mother, a &quot;born again&quot; co-worker of mine and others) would disagree with the assumption that those that do not regularly attend church are not as devout, but of course there is no way in any survey to &quot;prove&quot; this. The folks (all adults interviewed 1:1) were taken at their word if I understand correctly and asked to describe their religious activity and beliefs. Descriptions of what is meant by evangelical vs. born again is on the Barna site. Indeed, many can claim to be religious and not mean it, but then so could the atheists and buddhists. I think everyone who claims to be xian believes s/he is and practices according to her/his beliefs about this. <br>
<br>
Now to be fair there was a huuuuuge hubbub in xian circles after this as they considered it to be a wake up call that folks weren't getting the right message in church, were bowing to social pressures and trends rather than god's word etc. I get way less questioning of the results (perhaps since Barna is a recognized xian research group) than I do reactions from religious groups and leaders trying to address these. Frankly, I'm more impressed by that too. It would be easy for them to live in denial or pick things apart rather than recognize what George Barna himself described as a trend among xians and address in within their own communities and churches. Kudos to the group for their honesty and openness with the results.<br>
<br>
<br>
2. Did the people who got a divorce say when they got it? The divorces were with people already religious, though perhaps some religious folks found they could not continue in their beliefs or denom with a partner who was either never committed or grew away from religion and god. It's possible, but not the main reason. More likely, as Barna points out there is a trend to be more &quot;liberal&quot; in biblical interpretation and law. My grandma NEVER ate meat on Friday, cooked on Sunday or touched the host at Mass. My mother will try to eat fish on Friday, does whatever on Sunday and doesn't believe she has to go to Mass at all to be with god. As time goes on and society changes, so do our beliefs about marriage, commitment and how strictly we must follow rules...perhaps even god's rules. <br>
<br>
My two cents on why these may have been the results. Again--I'm not asserting that being Baptist makes you divorce or that atheism guarantees a good marriage. I absolutely agree that having both partners on the same page and agreeing about roles, child rearing etc. up front goes a loooong way in helping and admire the Catholics greatly for their marital counseling. What I am saying is that being committed to god and your xianity makes you no better prepared to marry or likely to stay married than my atheism.<br>
<br>
