<br>
My thoughts were that those who are truly committed to their religion are less likely to get divorced than those who are &quot;religious&quot; in name only.  And the reason that Atheists had lower numbers too is that they have consciously thought about their philosophical theories and are living consistently with their own morals.  People who are &quot;undecided&quot; or not living consistently with their ideals have already demonstrated that they lack commitment, and IMO are more likely to choose the easy out. <br>
<br>
The ideals that the Proclamation on Families express if applied make the marriage that you are in more successful.  And I would suggest that all things being equal, a couple who practices the ideals that are expressed have a greater chance than a marriage where they are not.  If all Mormons practiced the doctrine in the Proclamation, I would be willing to bet that the divorce rate would be significantly lower than it is see e the same mistakes that all people do including selfishness, adultry, unfortunately even spousal abuse. <br>
