<br>
I find the traditional view of christians about the man/woman role in marriage to resemble a parent/child relationship. I don't see how that can be healthy. Even when you have love and respect on both sides I don't see how having one partner being the person who has to submit to the authority of the other in all things (rather then each taking turns) can be anything but a parent/child relationship. How...unfullfilling.<br>
<br>
Now I, myself, to preform most of a traditional wife's job. I stay at home (my choice and preferrence). I do most of the cooking (I want to eat). I do most of the household chores. This actually is a point of contention in my family and one I want to see addressed because its wearing on me and due to taking out the recycling the other day we had a major problem here at home (my 2 year old locked me out of the house). <br>
<br>
But aside from practical roles my dh and I are equal partners in this marriage. Neither of us puts out wants and wishes above the other and for the most part take turns submitting to the other's wishes. He isn't head of the house. He does not make the finally decision in family questions. We make them together. We equally participate in this marriage. <br>
<br>
I grew up in a large family who the majority of them are practicing catholics (well mom's side is catholic and episcopole (sp)). I am taking about a HUGE family. My Dad is one of seven. His mother is one of seven. HUGE. (his mom's family is mostly baptist I think). One uncle was divorced and had the marriage annuled. The wife cheated like on the third day of marriage. Bad business. And one aunt married a divorced man. That's it. Divorce just wasn't something the family did. <br>
<br>
I think family background does contribute to divorce rates. I have had the luck of seeing family members work things out. Its nice. It helps me work things through with my DH when we are having troubles. <br>
<br>
But it also can be a problem. My sister and I were talking about how there has been times in her marriage when she might have wanted to leave her husband (I would not call it a healthy marriage) but hasn't because she worries how it would be accepted plus she does not want to hear Dad say &quot;I told you so&quot; or anything along those lines. I don't think he would say it to her, but he probably would to someone else. He doesn't like her husband. Doesn't think he's good enough for her.But then he doesn't think my DH is good enough for me. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
When my MIL found out my FIL had been cheating on her for years she refused to consider divorce because it wasn't biblical (in her mind though I've heard it here said that it is allowed in adultry). Their marriage is ... so unhealthy in my mind. And I think its sad that people stay in a marriage that isn't healthy for either partner because of religion. Its one thing to try and work things out, but this marriage is like watching an illness. <br>
<br>
I think marriage is good when its founded in similar principles with each partner. Mutual respect. When religion enters into it, if both partners respect the other's belief then it can be a strenght, but if one partner thinks the other needs to be changed in some way....I think that is the problem...and probably the source of the higher divorce rates over athiest. We all know if you go into a marriage thinking you can change the other person you are doomed to fail.<br>
