So much to respond to, I will start from the leftovers off the other thread....Ians1mom, I am sorry if you don't like me not respecting a woman who chooses to submit.  I would no more respect a slave who chose to submit or a parent that would not defend their child or a person who refused to think.  Do you realize that until the early 80's it wasn't illegal for a man to rape his wife?  You may chose to stay at home and raise a family, and that I do endorse.  I endorse it so very much that my wife and I practice it ourselves.  She is a SAHM and I am a breadwinner.  She submits to me as much as the sun submits to you.  You don't have to submit to do each acording to their ability.  You can do it as equals.  The minute you point out to me that you would never tell another woman she has to do what you do, we stop having a disagreement.  (Which you did so hardly anything I say applies to you personally.) What I disagree with are those who presume that the man-woman, breadwinner-domestic scheme is the ONLY way or that any other way is inferior.  That is condescending and self-righteous.  To answer your question about why I see wives as slaves to their husbands acording to your faith if not your practice is because (brace yourself Leah) Heather is right.  The bible is pretty clear about male superiority and womens status as chattel.<br>
<br>
Paige - do I believe my marriage is a property contract?  I believe that is what the document filed with the court is, but that is not what my marriage is.  My wife and I lived together before we were married, and I was commited to her before any paper came into it.  To tell you the truth, that document has hardly anything to do with my relationship to my wife.  It has far more to do with our relationship to our insurance carrier than how we see each other.  As far as 2 parents at home, loving and raising kids, well duh, obviously it is better for a kid than parents who despise one another or one parent who has to be away earning a living.  Then again, 4 parents who love each other would be better still (picture your inlaws moving in) and I know several families with their extended family in the home.  Mostly asian and hindu (which oddly have the lowest rates of divorce!)<br>
<br>
Misty - I am sorry if you think us citing statistics in refutation of an unfounded claim is some kind of superiority complex.  It isn't.  The only marriage and divorce rate I care about is my own. If someone takes a position that is unsupported by the facts (xians are more moral, xians have happier marriags, xians are smarter, make more money, commit less crimes, whatever) it doesn't matter to me if the group disproving them is buddhist, atheist or martian.  I care about the facts and reality.  Unfortunately, most of my facts are either xian or athiest oriented, because that was what I was and what I am now so that is where my exposure and knowledgebase arise.  Let me ask you this though, if an xian had stastics supporting that they were more moral, commited less crimes, earned more money, lived longer, had better hair and generally smelled nicer, do you think they would hesitate to roll them out?  Do you think I should be embarassed that the facts support my lifestyle and never mention it?  Or should I be pleased that my care and hard work appear to be pointing me in the right direction for a happy and successful life?<br>
<br>
Heather - this is twice in the same post, but here goes...&gt;You are right.  You cannot have 2 chiefs.  If you have a cheif somebody has to be an indian.  My question though is why have a cheif?  You also cite a great deal of scripture that pretty clearly says women must submit.  I don't see where it says women are smart or needed (your quotes say &quot;good thing&quot; and &quot;helpmate&quot;, nothing about smart there) but it rings clear and loud that women are to serve men.  As you said, if the others aren't listening to you, they aren't following the bible.<br>
<br>
Okay, on to the correlation of stastics.  A single study, like a single person can be flawed and not representative of reality.  If I were to tell a xian I was going to choose an avatar of their faith as a role model and selected Bill Clinton, that wouldn't be representitive. (Then again, maybe it would be?)  Yet if I took 4,000 men and bill was one of them, it would more closely relate.  So, you don't take a single study (or if you do, investigate the funding, very revealing) you are better served by taking SEVERAL studies and interpreting the mass as a body.  If one study says when xians pray for the sick they recover better, this is a positive correlation.  If another study says when they pray people get worse, this is a negative correlation.  Yet if you have multiple studies of reasonable quality and they each point in different directions, yoiu have NO correlation, which means the cause and event were unrelated.<br>
<br>
The one thing we can count on is that people change over time.  None of us are the same person we were 20 years ago.  I was a faithful xian 20 years ago, who could guess!  If you hold your faith more tightly than your marriage, you have handicapped your chances.  The choice of spouse should be based on compatibility (which requires clear understanding of what is compatible, I don't feel the bible is conducive to clarity with all the disputes among xians)  commitment and respect.  The nice thing about being an atheist is we can agree on what is truth and as we grow and change we can keep our eyes on that truth and reality to keep us safe.  I just wish xians could do that.<br>
